Citation.sAbstract: The aqueous solubilities of bisphenol A (BPA) in water and water + surfactants have been determined at four  different temperatures, 298.15 K, 303.15 K, 308.15 K, and 313.15 K. Results showed that the presence of a  cationic surfactant cetyltrimethylammonium bromide (CTAB) caused a significant increase in the solubility of  BPA, which increased linearly with the concentration of CTAB. When the anionic surfactants sodium  dodecylbenzenesulfonate (SDBS) and dodecyl sodium sulfate (SDS) were added to the solutions, the minimum  in the solubility of BPA was found at a lower concentration. However, when a certain concentration was exceeded,  a most striking increase in solubility was observed. The sequence of solubility enhancement as a function of the  critical micelle concentration is SDS greater than CTAB greater than SDBS at 298.15 K and negatively correlates to the hydrophilic  lipophilic balance of the surfactants.
Citation.sTitle: The Solubility Behavior of Bisphenol A in the Presence of Surfactants
